+  // =============================================================================
+  // LOCAL PATCH — Firefox newPage race fix
+  //   Patched by HushBox via patches/playwright-core@1.58.2.patch
+  //
+  // Bug being fixed
+  // ---------------
+  // The upstream version of this function was:
+  //
+  //   async doCreateNewPage() {
+  //     const { targetId } = await this._browser.session.send('Browser.newPage', ...);
+  //     return this._browser._ffPages.get(targetId)._page;
+  //   }
+  //
+  // `_ffPages` is populated by `_onAttachedToTarget` (see ~line 114 in this
+  // file), a separate event handler bound in the FFBrowser constructor:
+  //
+  //   this.session.on('Browser.attachedToTarget', this._onAttachedToTarget.bind(this));
+  //
+  // The upstream code assumes that by the time the `Browser.newPage` response
+  // is resolved, the `Browser.attachedToTarget` event for the new target has
+  // already been processed and the map has an entry for `targetId`. That
+  // assumption is not guaranteed by Firefox's Juggler protocol. Both messages
+  // travel the same WebSocket and are inherently ordered by arrival, but
+  // Playwright's protocol layer can resume the awaiting send() before the
+  // queued attach-event handler runs. When the response wins, `.get(targetId)`
+  // returns undefined and `.{_page}` throws:
+  //
+  //   TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading '_page')
+  //
+  // The same race surfaces as "Target page, context or browser has been
+  // closed" when the target is attached then immediately detached before the
+  // upstream code reads from the map.
+  //
+  // Why Chromium and WebKit do not show this
+  // ----------------------------------------
+  // crBrowser.js (`doCreateNewPage` at ~line 317) and wkBrowser.js (~line 213)
+  // have identical code shape — `return this._browser._crPages/_wkPages
+  // .get(targetId)._page;`. They work because CDP and the WK Playwright
+  // protocol both guarantee the target-attached event is dispatched before
+  // the create-target reply resolves. Juggler does not make that guarantee.
+  //
+  // Why we patch instead of waiting for upstream
+  // --------------------------------------------
+  // Two upstream reports of this exact stack, both closed without fixes:
+  //   https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/issues/35125 (closed not-planned)
+  //   https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/issues/36594 (closed)
+  // A five-year-old longstanding family of "Firefox newPage hangs/times out":
+  //   #3939 (2020), #9788 (2021), #28431 (2023), #36551 (2025) — all closed
+  //   without a fix.
+  // The race is still present on main: PR #34002 (Dec 2024) refactored this
+  // code path but kept the same `_ffPages.get(targetId)._page` pattern.
+  // Maintainers do not appear to treat it as a real bug, so we ship the fix
+  // ourselves.
+  //
+  // What this patch does
+  // --------------------
+  // 1. Arms a deferred listener for `Browser.attachedToTarget` BEFORE sending
+  //    `Browser.newPage`. Setting up the listener after the response would
+  //    reintroduce the race we are trying to fix. The listener filters by
+  //    browserContextId so concurrent newPage calls on other contexts cannot
+  //    resolve our deferred.
+  // 2. Fast path: if the map is already populated when the response lands,
+  //    returns immediately — same behavior as upstream when the race wins.
+  // 3. Slow path: if the map is empty, waits for the attach event with a
+  //    30-second timeout. The timeout surfaces true protocol stalls (which
+  //    are a separate Firefox bug, see #3939) instead of hanging on the
+  //    default test timeout.
+  // 4. If the target was attached then immediately detached before init
+  //    completed, throws a clear error instead of the original cryptic
+  //    TypeError. (Symptom of `_onDetachedFromTarget` running between the
+  //    attach event and our map read.)
+  // 5. Cleans up the event listener in a `finally` block so we never leak.
+  //
+  // What this patch does NOT fix
+  // ----------------------------
+  // The separate "Browser.newPage hangs and never replies" failure mode
+  // (upstream #3939, #36551). That is a protocol-level stall inside Firefox,
+  // not a JS-layer race. Tests timing out on newPage hang for >45s are a
+  // different problem and need a different remedy.
+  //
+  // Removal criteria
+  // ----------------
+  // Delete this patch when:
+  //   (a) Upstream Playwright merges a fix that makes `doCreateNewPage`
+  //       deterministic — periodically check the linked issues, and
+  //   (b) `e2e/firefox-newpage-race.spec.ts` passes against the new
+  //       upstream version without the patch under heavy parallel load.
+  // =============================================================================
